ğŸ’› The Arts, I freaking love ya. ğŸ’›  Tonight I want to appreciate 'The Arts'. Last night I spent an evening at Hamer Hall in Melbourne to see 'The Waifs'. A band I would often see live back in the day,  once when John Butler took my breath away as their support act. A band that I listened to when falling in love with my hubby.  Last night I heard the most incredible music in a space that I was prevlidged to graduate Art School in. A place where I had the most memorable evening spent with my Dad seeing James Taylor whom was always playing in our house growing up (mostly at the end of the night or party) And with all of these memories going through my head then out came the fiddle. All I could hear was one sound in a room of a couple of thousand. An instrument that brings back memories of my beautiful Grandma playing when ever I sang to her. With all of this in my mind and heart I cried like a baby in the concert last night. Seriously. And I'm ok with that. Why? This is the power The Arts can have. Whether it's visual arts, music, film, theatre .....The Arts. I freaking love ya!!! Who's with me?

Ingredients  1 lb. linguine or fettuccine  6 tbsp. olive oil  12 oz. mixed mushrooms, thinly sliced  3 cloves garlic, finely chopped  1/4 c. nutritional yeast  2 green onions, thinly sliced on an angle  Directions  Cook linguine as label directs, reserving 3/4 cups pasta cooking water before draining. Return drained linguine to pot.  Meanwhile, in 12" skillet, heat oil on medium-high. Add mushrooms and garlic; cook 5 minutes or until mushrooms are browned and tender, stirring. Transfer to pot with cooked, drained linguine along with nutritional yeast, reserved cooking water, 1/2 teaspoon salt and 3/4 teaspoon coarsely ground pepper. Toss until well combined. Garnish with green onions.  Enjoy!

Please have a read of this, thank you @emilyskyefit ğŸ™ğŸ¼ #behappywithyourself ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ» Sometimes I look like the pic on the left, sometimes times I look like the pic on the right. - I don't always have abs or look lean and I'm never "perfect". .  So many people are aiming for this idea of "perfection"... but what exactly is perfection?  I used to beat myself up for not being perfect (whatever that is). I'd actually feel like my "worth" was less if I didn't look a certain way. My goal at one stage was to get rid of my belly fat so that when I sat I'd have no "rolls" - now I see how ridiculous and superficial I was being. Yes there's no denying, I like to look good, as most people do but it's not healthy when it becomes an obsession and your "self worth" is attached to your appearance. I've just returned from being overseas for a month. I ate what I wanted and enjoyed it, I also gained a bit of extra body fat which isn't a big deal because my lifestyle nowadays isn't about restricting myself & I like it that way. ğŸ˜#noregrets . Life isn't perfect and neither are we. I love myself no matter how I look and it's this self love that motivates me to make changes in my life so I can feel my best... like exercising and eating nutritious food (& treats for mental health hehe). ğŸ˜ I was once sitting at a fitness shoot and was told by someone (while pointing at my belly) "Fitness models don't have belly rolls when they sit" - I was so upset about this & felt so inadequate and this only led to me being more obsessed with being "perfect" or as "lean" as I could be. Nowadays I know better. My priority is how I feel mentally and physically and I won't sacrifice that to look a certain way OR to get the approval from anyone else! Please consider what goes into a photograph you see online or in magazines... and also what goes into looking a certain way, for example; posing, angles, lighting & even photoshopping! A lot of what we see in these images is not "healthy" or "realistic" and comparing ourselves will never do us any good. Focus on your health - mental and physical and focus on being YOUR best.

With so many cafes opening across Melbourne, you have to stand out from the crowd for people to be lining up out the door, and No. 19 certainly has the X-factor.  The striking interior draws you in with its natural light, hand-painted teal tiles, brass details, and concrete surfaces all of which come together to pay homage to Greek delicatessens that populated Melbourne in the 1950s.  Owned by local couple Domanic and Diana Caruso, the space is the creation of local design firm Biasol. "Our concept was inspired by the Greek delicatessens that flourished around Melbourne in the 1950s," said the Biasol team. "Materially, concrete surfaces - the counter, walls and floor - give the space a warmth and sophistication." Read more on neoskosmos.com

So this week I finished a project with an inspiring company @timeivchangewatches who are creating change through their collection of handcrafted watches.  Their entire collection is made from vegan leather including a range of pineapple leather "Pinatex" watches. Their watch cases are designed out of 100% recycled aluminium. And to top it off, they give back 20% of their profits to 9 organisations pushing for positive change. From sanctuaries to vegan emergency relief operations.  This project really opened my eyes up to the harm that leather production has not just on the animals whose lives it takes. But on the people who work in the tanneries and the surrounding communities. Not to mention l the strain it puts on our environment due to the huge water resources animal leather production needs.  Time IV Change took the idea of  creating #veganwatches and made it a reality. They achieved their kickstarter campaign in just 7 days. And now they're the world's first vegan watch company!  Just one year on, their watches sell out in just hours! And they have the very nice problem of not being able to keep up with demand. ğŸ‘ŒğŸ½ It was a pleasure to write their story and help architect a user experience for this positive  movement.  And if you'd like to find out more about their story and watch range head to: www.timeivchange.com.au  #bethechange

Brooklyn Depot Melbourne is a New York-inspired sports bar just off the north end of Hardware Lane, with a large central bar surrounded by benches, tables and booths.  The Brooklyn Classic burger is their base model burger with everything after that getting quite extreme with pork belly, lamb, pulled chicken, turkey and mushroom burgers all on offer.  Brooklyn Classic was difficult to photograph. It comes with lettuce, tomato and Depot special sauce, but fillings are quite scarce and everything is hidden inside that massive, seeded milk bun. The beef was rich and juicy, perfectly cooked and well seasoned. The cheese was amazing and gooey, melted over the top. The sauce was plentiful and gave a great tang. But salad items were lost, not crunchy, and rather pointless here. The milk bun had a lot of flavour in itself and the sweetness was slightly overpowering for this simple burger.  A side of fries can be added to your burger order. Not shown in this photo, I also ordered a basket of Phat Chips which were absolutely delicious, crunchy outside, fluffy inside, and seasoned with plenty of chilli sea salt for a spicy zing.  The venue has a great vibe, the food is delicious and service was great. I look forward to trying some other burger options here later in the year, or just popping in for drinks.  #burger #food #melbourne #newyork #sportsbar

Who is the real Aussie?  This picture was taken during my trip to Melbourne, and there is a context to it.  The cameleers were camel drivers, mostly from Afghanistan, India and Pakistan and they helped explore the outback and helped establish rail networks. They basically ran the outback for 70 years and not many people know they existed.  This particular gentleman is Monga Khan. He applied for an exemption from the white Australia policy about 100 years ago. He is particularly heroic and symbolic in highlighting struggle of all those who made it possible to make Australia the diverse land that it is.  #australia #aussiesofinstagram #aussie #history #melbourne #victoria #afghanistan #India #Indian #historic #heroic #hero #struggle #hustle #diversity #culture #nation #story #storytelling #streetart #streetphotography #mobilephotography #travelphotography #travel #traveller #travelling #travels #lifelessons

MELBOURNE // @studio_twocan is a creative studio, managed by sisters, Maddie and Becc Sharrock. Every Studio Twocan piece is individually handcrafted with care and precision. Their cement ceramics range was refined over two years. It has taken time to  perfect their products, which shows their dedication and commitment to quality of design and manufacture. They colour the cement using pigment to create an organic layering inspired by Australian landscapes. Each piece is polished with natural oils, sealing the cement with a satin finish. This process celebrates imperfections and ensures that each piece is unique. Butler was the first black woman to come to international prominence as a science fiction writer. Incorporating powerful, spare language and rich, well-developed characters, her work tackled race, gender, religion, poverty, power, politics, and science in a way that touched readers of all backgrounds. Butler was a towering figure in life and in her art and the world noticed; highly acclaimed by reviewers, she received numerous awards, including a MacArthur "genius" grant, both the Hugo and Nebula awards, the Langston Hughes Medal, as well as a PEN Lifetime Achievement award. #embiggenbooks #books #melbourne #scifi #bookstagram

Ok that was one of the strangest comedy shows I have ever seen... (spoiler alert and trigger warning) It starts off with the comedian jumping on a treadmill while in the background on a projector he is being chased by a gorilla. The monkey represents the primitive part of is mind, his fears. He stays on the treadmill for the whole show and does comedy. But what starts out as comedy becomes a story about his life and how he was date raped... and it is a serious story, presented as a comedy. It has it's funny moments but it was so contrasting, and the fact he was on his treadmill getting healthy and trying to be positive made it all the more weird. I thought he was brave and it was a clever show, it was just totally unexpected. I also liked that he used comedy to explain a difficult subject that obviously had a profound effect on him. There was recordings of his therapy sessions among other things. He even made a point of saying "I know this is a comedy festival, I was hesitant but they insisted". It was an interesting show and unlike anything I have ever seen. I'm not surprised it has won awards... #comedy #Melbourne #survivor #acmi

Portrait 189/1000: Dave Shepherd. Dave is one of the owners of @essenza_cafes, a brilliant little cafe in Healesville's main street. The space the cafe now occupies was once a walkway between two storefronts, and it's now a beautiful, cosy cafe space with excellent coffee and a place to sit out of the heat and noise of the main street. I remember going there after it opened and thinking it was a very Melbourne-esque cafe for the town, and a great thing to have open. Since then, I've had countless coffees there and gotten to know Dave and the staff there pretty well. Brad, one of the baristas there, was my 100th portrait. Dave's always been lovely to catch up with over that time, and I barrelled up to him on the street a last year and asked if I could take his portrait for the project. He generously obliged and we took this right out the front of the cafe. Thank you for your time, David! Keep up the excellent work (and coffee!).

I fill up my plate more and more and do more and more and still - some people like to tell me what they think I should do. The key here however, those people who are telling me what to do - are not doing themselves. So until they put themselves in your shoes or actually risk it a little, open up their minds a little or even realise that their way isn't the be all and end all and actually realise that we are all unique and the beautiful thing about life is - you can do whatever the hell you want - then just keep doing. Be obsessed with what makes you happy regardless. Amazing things can happen at the drop of a hat if you just do! Anyone in your life right now who seems to tell you how to live? Pineapple Shrimp fried rice bowl recipe: Ingredients:  1 1/2 cups (uncooked) brown rice 1 tsp oil 1.25 lb shrimp, shelled and deveined, (1lb after peeled) chopped into chunks 1 1/2 cups fresh pineapple, cut into small chunks 5 large scallions, chopped 3 cloves garlic, minced 1 fresh chili pepper or jalepeno, chopped 2 tsp soy sauce (or more to taste) 1 tbsp fish sauce  cilantro for garnish Directions:  Cook brown rice according to package directions and set aside to cool. Cut a pineapple in half and hollow out both halves to make two bowls.  Heat a nonstick wok on high heat; when hot add oil. Add shrimp and cook a few minutes until almost cooked though.  Add chilli/scallops/garlic.  Saute about a minute, then add the rice and pineapple and stir a few times. Add soy sauce and fish sauce, stir to mix all the ingredients and cook another 30 seconds. Four GEICO Skytypers performing at last weekend's Melbourne Air and Space Show. This was actually the second image I took all day, and it ended up being one of my favorites. Photo taken Saturday April 1, 2017. Following description of the aircraft is credit geicoskytypers.com: "The GEICO Skytypers fly the SNJ-2 version of the aircraft. This model has an enlarged 180 gallon fuel tank allowing the aircraft to operate for more than four hours.  Other unique design elements of this particular aircraft include: a decrease of eight inches in the overall length, a larger round rudder,  and a free-castering tail wheel. Each plane weighs 5500 pounds and utilizes a 600hp Pratt and Whitney R-1340-AN-1, 9 cylinder radial engine.  This remarkable and versatile aircraft was an evolution of the NAAâ€™s BC-1 basic combat trainer. 174 BC-1s were first produced in 1937 for the U.S. Army Aircorp.  These aircraft also utilized fixed landing gear. The BC-1 was designed by North American as a low-cost trainer with all the characteristics of a high-speed fighter. While not as fast as a fighter, it was simple to maintain and repair, had more maneuverability and was easier to handle than previous models. A pilotâ€™s airplane, it could roll, loop, spin, snap, and vertical roll. It was designed to provide the best possible training in all types of tactics, from ground strafing to bombardment to aerial dog-fighting. The aircraft also contained versatile equipment such as bomb racks, blind flying instrumentation, gun and standard cameras, fixed and flexible guns, and just about every other device that military pilots had to operate at that time."

Portrait 195/1000: Joel Hawting. Joel is a pastor at Liberty Family Church in Healesville. He and I first met when the church was running events to raise money as part of World Vision Australia's 40 Hour Famine, and because he's involved in events and projects around town, we end up talking pretty often and he's been in the paper a few times as a result. This photo was actually taken for a newspaper article, because Joel and several other people in town had made a team for Movember Foundation Australia. This photo was taken at the start of the month, with a bit of shadow on his face; his team had a goal of growing horseshoe moustaches, and grow them they did. Thanks for your time, Joel!  Note: My photo schedule got waaaay out of whack and this got posted the other day. My bad!

Zinc testing. Zinc deficiencies is more common than we realise. It can lead to dozens of health conditions. Many people are unaware of the importance of this mineral. M I L K  T H E  C O W ğŸ„  Having heard amazing things about this reputable fromagerie, we got together a group of girls to go get us some wine and cheese (yassssss!). Their Carlton location is home is a massive five metre cheese cabinet with over 150 cheeses on offer. Inside was packed, so our lovely waiter Lucas made sure we were comfortable outside with some super soft blankets.  You can opt for a cheese flight board matched with your drink of choice here, but this time around we decided to build our own. Top cheese of the night was definitely the oak smoked cheddar, but if you're into soft cheeses, loved the triple cream brie. Prosciutto was thinly sliced and a great addition, we also recommend the quince!  Love that this place is open until 1am, great to sit down and catch up with friends at. We do recommend asking for paired drinks as after selecting our own drinks we realised they were overshadowed by how good the cheese was. Service is knowledgable and super friendly. We really enjoyed ourselves and will be back!  Atmosphere: 3.75/5  Price: $50 for two people  Food: 4/5

We took advantage of the warmth today to check out the new Maritime Cove Community Park playground at Perce White Reserve in Port Melbourne. It's covered in sand and has sand play stations and a loopy loop slide similar to Ron Barassi Snr Park playground, and rope courses, climbing frames and water play stations similar to Royal Park playground. These new modern playground designs are awesome! I was surprised at how big the place was! There are so many different stations to play at...and even exercise equipment for adults right at the end! Here are my kids at the toddler sand play section. There is easy parking right in front of the playground, and a great bonus is that Sandridge Beach is literally meters away! There will never be a time I will ever get over having twins. There will never be a time that I don't look at this perfect bunch and think..'wow! I can't believe I made all that!'. As much as they test me and push my boundaries into areas I never knew existed, they have taught me more than I anticipated.  They taught me that life prior to children was actually never hard, I just never knew what hard was... they taught me that I can actually survive on 4-5 hours sleep...regularly,  they taught me to be stronger emotionally, they taught me what self control actually is...especially when you scream 'FFS!!' 57469 times a day and it's all said in your mind,  they taught me that not only can I run? I can do it pushing 50kg,  they taught me to juggle 2000 things at a time,  to still be happy when I cook food that they say is 'disgusting', they taught me that washing my hair only twice a week is still ok,  They taught me to cherish moments, to be grateful for my and their health, and oh so much more.  I sometimes sit by their beds at night and promise them to be better or try harder tomorrow, and each day I wake up, I remind myself to always be better than any situation gives me, especially if it is too much for me to handle at any given moment.  I am loving holidays and they are with me all the time and the rush of kinder is not being missed!  But I look at this picture? And I'm just so proud, as these 3 little babies are my biggest accomplishment yet. . . . . #onestongmum #meplus3 #babies #twinmum #lifelessons #parenting #grateful #family #3babies #melbourne #melbournemum #fitmum

5 years ago I was lucky to be invited to cook a dinner at Attica with this wonderful person. We were planning a dish with skate to be a part of the menu and as the size and type of skate available to us was causing us trouble Ben admitted to me in a cautious and polite way that honestly, he wouldn't have put that on his own menu since it was threatened by extinction. I felt I had to take it off the menu, anything else would have been disrespectful, and we cooked a dish on beautiful local mussels instead.  Once I got home I started studying the subject and realizing how little informed I actually was. Skate never saw the menu since and that incident shaped me and inspired me to take more responsibility.  Yesterday night I had the pleasure of dining at @atticamelbourne again and another wonderful experience there of passion and professionalism reminded me once again how keeping true to yourself while working hard for your dreams is the biggest achievement to strive for. Quinces - you know it's autumn when the quinces arrive ğŸKeen jam and paste makers should note that the quince's pectin content is always higher at the start of the season. Pears - we're starting to see a handover from the #summer varieties, like William pears, to the #winter varieties like Packham and Burre Bosc. When you decide to be raw, authentic and share yourself on social media - you have to open up to criticism. Now, I don't even have many followers or claim to have people that are interested in my life anymore than they are yours - but my choices, my decisions - inspire some, confuse many, and cause concern (it seems) for others. There are some people in my home town who have been asking my friends if I am "okay", based on my Instagram posts. I can only assume these concerned folks are talking about the kink posts, and perhaps the idea that I've sold all my material belongings and jet setted across the world without much warning. You may not understand me, you may not understand my decisions - and I know, as a mature and clear minded person, that you are not asking to cause drama, but because you are interested, you are intrigued. You are curious. You want to know more. So, just in case there is anyone else who wants to question my friends about my wellbeing, here it is - I am doing great, I am safe, I am empowered, I am empowered sexually (and if you don't understand that, it's okayâ˜ºï¸), I am happy and authentic and I feel very free. If anyone is intrigued or concerned, or wants to ask me any questions then - I am an open book :) And please, remember - we are all interesting in our own unique ways, we all have different realities, and if something intrigues you or threatens your reality, you do not have to understand it, you do not have to make sense of it, but you do need to be kind and respectful of other people and their choices. ğŸ˜˜ #melbourne #kind #respect #peace #love

Swipe â†’ to see all  I've been seeing a fair few of these posts lately. The general concensus on dieting is that it must be this tedious, unenjoyable process of self torture which eventually leads to loss of complience via binging or just forfeiting your diet.  Understand that progress is made through consistency over time. Weight loss and weight gain are merely a game of numbers. Calories in vs calories out, and the manipulation of macronutrients.  What you eat is not important when it comes to building muscle and losing fat. The ratio of fat, carbohydrate and protein intake and total calorie intake are what is important.  If you want to lose weight, you must be in a calorie deficit.  If you want to gain weight, you need to be in a calorie surplus.  There are plenty of calculators out there to estimate your starting macros. However, undersrsnd that this is a process of trial and error, and more often than not, your macros will change on a week to week basis.  If you are unsure as where to start. I reccomend you start by merely tracking what you are eating now. Track what intake is over a few days and compare those days. Take an average for what you currently hit. Begin to understand what is going into your body.... this can be good practice for when you need to refine the process.  Use an app: I use MyFitnessPal for my macro counting.  Ask for help: I run a fexible dieting coaching service. Inquires via the email in the bio of my profile.  Feel free to tag a friend you believe would benefit from this advice. My main goal here is to educate. I wish to reach as many people as possible.  Let's all smash our goals together, and enjoy the process.

My exhibition 'Friends and Beasts' is now in full swing at Tacit Contemporary Art in Abbotsford. It's a show that celebrates my love of animals with classic black and white images capturing a moment of connection. There is also a series of smaller abstract studies that explore the beauty of feathers, fur, skin and scales. These samples show just a few of the framed and unframed limited edition fine art prints for sale. The gallery closes for Easter between 10-18 April, so today would be the perfect opportunity to see the exhibition between 11am and 5pm. Enjoy!

The Northcote Social Club started life as the Commercial Hotel. Following the Maritime Strike of 1890, during the height of Labour-Capital tensions in 1891, the hotel played host to the first meeting of the Northcote Workingman's Democratic Association. The organisation was dedicated to 'mutual assistance, promotion of a brotherhood of affection, unanimity of thought and action in matters affecting the social and political welfare of the working classes and the propagation of an Australian democracy.' The association became the first branch of Trades Hall's Progressive Political League, a precursor to the Labor Party. The locals told me this tree fell last year after a storm hit the island . . . Some said to let it go. A man and his friend said it still had life in it and to give it a chance. The ones who said let it go didn't bother to help when the two men decided to help it back up. They packed sand bags around it and put the tree between two sticks. It was droopy and lifeless. But everyday in between their shifts they would stop by, talk to it and water it. For months it looked helpless, but then the same tree started to grow leaves. And it eventually started looking like this. They told me, it should be back to its old self, if not stronger in a few more months.  I loved hearing this story. In this story, the perseverance of the tree and the faith these two men had in it really inspired me to keep going and have faith in my journey. Some days I feel unsure of where I'm headed, but I guess if we were to figure it all out today. Where would be the fun in that?

Vietnamese Beef Pho for this rainy Melbourne evening ğŸ²  Recipe: 2L GF beef stock 3 thick slices ginger 1 onion, thinly sliced 3 garlic cloves, sliced 3 star anise 2 cinnamon quills, bruised 4 peppercorns 2 tbsp caster sugar 1/3 cup fish sauce 375g flat rice noodles 600g rump steak 1 cup bean sprouts 1 bunch watercress 4 spring onions, finely sliced 1/2 bunch coriander 1 red chilli, thinly sliced  1. Place stock + 500ml water in saucepan with ginger, onion, garlic, star anise, cinnamon, sugar and fish sauce 2. Bring to boil, then reduce heat to low and simmer for 30-40 mins 3. Prepare rice noodles, drain well 4. Use slotted spoon to remove ginger, garlic, cinnamon and star anise from broth 5. Season rump with salt and pepper and sear in hot pan (should be fairly rare) - allow to rest 6. Divide noodles and broth among soup bowls 7. Thinly slice rump and distribute between bowls 8. Top with bean sprouts, watercress, coriander, spring onion and chilli  Serves 4. Enjoy!!

#DearIwashere - #noblepark . . . Ini akelo, makanan Afrika yang dibuat dari tepung dan gandum. Lucunya, di Wikipedia makanan ini nggak tertulis. Makanan Afrika yang paling mirip sama ini dan bisa kita temuin kalo googling, namanya couscous. . Tapi kata Pak Stephen Nual, juru masaknya, akelo beda sama couscous. Couscous butirannya kecil-kecil, akelo lebih besar. Meskipun sekilas nggak keliatan banyak-banyak amat, makanan ini padet banget. #IkanPaus dan Dea makan sepiring berdua abis itu kekenyangan dan nggak makan lagi seharian. Kata Pak Nual, akelo emang dimakan kalau orang mau nempuh perjalanan panjang. Biar awet. Nggak laper-laper lagi di jalan. . Kami makan akelo pake ikan dan bumbu herbal-herbalan. Tapi sebenernya akelo kayak nasi atau roti, bisa dimakan pake apa aja termasuk yoghurt, lho, @iwashere_id. . Btw, kedai Pak Nual otentik banget. Mulai dari makanan, gaya nyusun interior, sampe interaksi antar manusianya. Terus kebanyakan yang nongkrong di sana bapak-bapak. Mereka pesen satu menu besar yang dimakan rame-rame. . Kalau Dea peratiin suasana di kedai Pak Nual mirip di lapo. Bapak-bapak di sana gaya ngobrol dan becandanya entah kenapa mirip ompung-ompung. . Salamatahari, semogaselaluhangat dan cerah, Sundea . #africanfood #food #lunch #kuliner #delicious #kenyang #wareg #melbourne #latepost #knowling .

We have said it before, but walking tours really are great for seeing a city in a short space of time. It was a sunny day in Melbourne, so pretty busy, but we were still able to learn a lot about the city's history. Favourite facts:  1- Melbourne 'conveniently' found gold about two weeks after separating from Sydney, which arguably triggered their rivalry, particularly as Melbourne subsequently became the richest city in the world during the 1880s gold rush.  2- Melbourne has not one, but two bank holidays for sporting events. The Melbourne Cup and AFL Grand Final both merit a day off work!  After the historical section, we also had chance to see the contemporary side of the city, including the legal street art, independent eateries and many arts buildings.

Every exercise in your program must serve a purpose... - Ask yourself: why am I performing X movement? - If you are performing any exercise for the hell of it, without a specific reason, then you're simply adding 'junk volume' to your training. - When training for strength and size, it is important to remember that every exercise in your program can either benefit or detriment your progress. Training for the sake of training or filling up time not only reduces your training economy (time wasting), but it may slow down your progress as a result of additional fatigue, which maybe unnecessary. - Take the hip thrust for example... It can: 1. Teach hip extension. 2. Add volume for the posterior chain - aka bigger and stronger glutes. 3. Serve rehab purposes. - Performing any exercise just because is a sure way to slow your progress, so make sure that everything you do in the gym can be justified! - #TeamJPS  #RaisingTheStandard - #bodybuilding #powerlifting #fitness #strength #strong #lift #gym #physique #training #lean #muscle #squat #bench #abs #ripped #aesthetic #deadlift #lean #iifym #flexibledieting #inspiration #motivation #muscle #results #personaltrainer #melbourne #portmelbourne #airportwest #portmelbournebeach

The Peacock Inn was the second hotel to open in Northcote after the Pilgrim Inn Hotel (now the Croxton Park). In its early days it was a common haunt for teamsters and draymen travelling to and from Northcote's brickworks. The Age reported in July 1937, a George Harvey of North Fitzroy was charged with illegal bookmaking in the pub's garage, averaging around 300 bets on race days. He was represented at court by John Galbally, a Collingwood footballer and founder of the law firm Galbally & O'Bryan. Galbally would later become a Labor Minister in the Cain Government, known for his social reforms and opposition to capital punishment. . .  #peacockinnhotel #peacockinn #thepeacock #peacock #pub #hotel #pubsofmelbourne #melbpubs #pubs #beer  #pubsofinstagram #northcote #highst #melb #melbourne #igersmelb #igmelb #igersmelbourne #igmelbourne #littlehistory #pubhistory #history #socialhistory #laborhistory #labourhistory #labor #aushistory #ozhistory #collingwoodfc @peacockinnhotel

Back Development:  To grow a thick and complete back a combination of exercises are needed. Heavy rows or heavy deadlifts are favourites of mine as they build thickness like no other. .  However to complete your back development more targeted exercises are necessary too. .  To build the width nothing beats a stiff arm pull down, you can get a huge range of motion and even bigger contraction through your lats when done correctly. .  Then to build the finer detail, nothing beats for me a unilateral (singe hand) row, this could be on a cable machine or a plate loaded machine or even with a dumbbell. They all work great! . Another burger post guyssss!! So a couple weeks ago when Melbourne decided to not be bipolar and give us a full day of sun so a friend and I decided to go smash a couple burgers. Not really knowing this side of town 100% yet and where the delicious burgers are located she suggested the infamous Fat Bob's @fatbobsbarandgrill in Moorabbin. This place is hidden away in sort of an industrial area but it was super packed and it made me excited, because a busy burger place is a good burger place!! Fat Bob's is an American style diner with a large range of burgers with a load more sides!! I ended up getting the Red Dog (double beef burger with extra Fat Bob's sauce) and she got some onion rings and some popcorn chicken!! And man when they came out my mouth was watering!! When the burger came out I was so hungry I nearly forgot to take a photo for you guys! It was super tasty and the flavour was really nice! The sides of onion rings and popcorn chicken was a bonus, they made the meal so much better, I should have gotten a milkshake to finish it off though, but there's always next time ;). Great service, great atmosphere and quick to table burgers to! I give it a solid 7.5/10ğŸ”ğŸ”, what a great way to finish off a beautiful  Melbourne day  Thanks @fatbobsbarandgrill for the big dirty burger! And see you guys again soon :) #fatbobsburgerandgrill #burgers #burgersfortheboys #doublepattie #reddog #macandcheese #burgersofmelbourne #melbourne #melbournefood #moorabbin #theburgercollective

Even though the view was mind blowing I still thought that I could you spent in those quids in a bar on beer and enjoyed much. I have seen the Ferris Wheel in many cities such as Singapore, Shanghai, a city called tianjin in China, in Germany, Melbourne, Maine USA and so on and so forth. Walking is a great way to boost your physical activity â€“ and your body will thank you in more ways than one. Energising, versatile and low-impact, walking is a great choice for anyone wanting to fit more physical cavity into their daily life. It can be done anytime and anywhere, and itâ€™s something that most people can do regardless of age or starting fitness levels. Plus, there are plenty of opportunities you can find to fit walking into your day, without necessarily thinking of it as exercise. Here are just some of the health benefits of walkingâ€¦ 1. It can make you live longer Well, thatâ€™s just about the ultimate health benefit, isnâ€™t it? Regular physical activity improves your chances of living a longer, healthier life, and a Harvard University study suggested that walking briskly for just 75 minutes a week can add almost two years to your life, while upping your steps to walk 2.5 hours a week can add more than seven years.  2. It helps keep your heart healthy Being active helps keep your heart in good condition. To reduce your risk of heart disease and high blood pressure, the Heart Foundation suggests aiming for 30 minutes of moderate activity such as walking on most if not all days of the week, if not all, and studies show that when it comes to cardiovascular health, a solid, brisk walk is as good as a run. People who walk regularly have fewer heart attacks and strokes, have lower blood pressure, and higher levels of healthy HDL cholesterol than those who are mostly sedentary. 3. It reduces your risk of diabetes A combination of daily exercise, a balanced diet and a healthy body weight can prevent 60% of type 2 diabetes cases. Regular walking is a great way to manage your weight, and therefore reduce your chances of developing this common condition. Plus, walking for 30 minutes a day makes your muscles more sensitive to insulin, which means betterblood sugar controlâ€“ which not only helps lower your risk of diabetes, it can also help you to manage the condition if you already have it. 4. It helps you lose and manage weight - what more incentive do you need :)

In the spirit of the season, I've been contemplating freedom. Last night's Seder, a six course meal for 22 people. Two days in the kitchen and then the mayhem of the meal. Even the 9 year old noted "it was like I was caged". What actually is freedom? My life is a charmed one. Freedom to make choices, determine my path, to do mainly as I please. But what of those who live under oppressive regimes, those whose lives are characterised by restriction, inequity, disadvantage? After 20 years working in human rights I know freedom to be a hard won right, yet still, for so many, it's not there, not even here, in this seemingly free bountiful country. Such a complicated world. So many questions, so much injustice.
